We investigated the potential use of SnO2 carbon nanofiber as anode material for lithium ion batteries. We have carried out cyclic voltammetry (CV) studies in the potential window of 0.01–2.0 V at a scan rate of 0.1 mV/s as depicted in Fig. 9a for initial five cycles. During the first cathodic scan an irreversible reduction peak with a maximum at 0.76 V is seen which is attributed to the reduction of SnO2 to metallic Sn and the formation of the solid electrolyte interphase (SEI) layer in the first cycle Eq. (1) (Ding et al. 2014; Reddy et al. 2013a, 2015; Yim et al. 2011; Zhu et al. 2011).1SnO2+4Li++4e-→Sn+2Li2O\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
